Total Daily Insulin Requirement (in units of insulin) 
TDI = 0.55 X Total Weight in Kilograms (Font: DTC, 2013)

Basal Insulin Dose 
BaID = (TDI - (20-25%)*TDI)/2 (Font: SBD, 2009) 
              or
       (40-50%)* TDI (Font: DTC, 2013)

Bolus Insulin Dose - Rule of "500" (Font: SBD, 2009; DTC, 2013)
BoID = 500 / TDI (obs.: Constant response to insulin: 1 unit insulin covers so many grams of carbohydrate)
Sugestion: In the breakfast insulin-to-carbohydrate ratio might be breakfast 1:8 grams, lunch 1:15 grams 
                  and dinner 1:12 grams.

Insulin Sensibility (IS) - Rule of "1800" (Font: SBD, 2009; DTC, 2013)
High Blood Sugar Correction Factor 
IS = 1800 / TDI (obs.: 1 unit of insulin will reduce the blood sugar so many mg/dl)
Sugestion: 1 unit insulin / blood sugar level by 40-50 mg/dl

Corrective Bolus Insulin Dose (Font: SBD, 2009; DTC, 2013)
CBoID = (CurrentGL - DesiredGL) / IS (obs.: CurrentGL and DesiredGL in mg/dl)

References: 
1. (SBD, 2009) SBD. Gerenciamento Eletrï¿½nico do Diabetes. In: GOMES, M. B.; LERARIO, A. C. (Eds.) 
                         Diretrizes da Sociedade Brasileira de Diabetes, SBDï¿½09, pp. 219-230, 2009.
2. (DTC, 2013) Available in: http://dtc.ucsf.edu/types-of-diabetes/type1/treatment-of-type-1-diabetes/
                         medications-and-therapies/type-1-insulin-therapy/calculating-insulin-dose/#formulas

When the insulin pump is at STOP state, it should not administer insulin. 
Insulin Pump only carries out the administration of insulin doses when in 
RUN state.
